QTM 151 Final Project: How did countries around the world respond to COVID-19?¶

COVID-19 and the Rights to Health and Education - Income and Region Analysis¶

Initial Exploration to Understand the Data¶

We used esr_hiy_globalbest.csv and esr_lmy_globalbest.csv, which contain data about the economic and social rights for high and low/middle income countries using the "global best" standard of assessment.

We knew we wanted to explore COVID-19, so we cleaned and analyzed the data to find the best rights to work with based on the number of "valid" high and low/middle income countries for each GBScore right. We defined a "valid country" as having data for pre-COVID (2019), during COVID (2020), and post-COVID/recovery period (2021) for that specific right.

Upon completion of this exploratory phase, we decided to focus on health and education, as these rights had the most number of "valid" high income countries (there were much fewer high than low/middle income countries).

Notes on ESR Columns¶

For health analysis we have several important metrics:

In High Income Countries (esr_hiy_globalbest):¶

HiY_Health_All_GBScore - Overall health score SeniorSurvival_All_MRValue - Senior survival rates U5Survival_All_MRValue - Under-5 survival rates NotLowBirWt_MRValue - Not low birth weight rates

In Low-Middle Income Countries (esr_lmy_globalbest):¶

LMY_Health_All_GBScore - Overall health score AdultSurvival_All_MRValue - Adult survival rates U5Survival_All_MRValue - Under-5 survival rates Contraception_MRValue - Contraception access

Data Cleaning to Choose Rights¶

Find the number of valid high income countries (high_income_countries) and low and middle income countries (low_income_countries) for each GBScore category. A valid country is one that has data for all three years of 2019, 2020, and 2021 for a specific GBScore right (Quality of Living, Education, Food, Health, Housing, Work).

First: high income countries¶

In [8]:
# Data for all high income countries during 2019, 2020, 2021
high_income_countries = esr_hiy_globalbest[esr_hiy_globalbest['High_Income_Country'] == 1]['Country'].unique()
high_income_covid = esr_hiy_globalbest[(esr_hiy_globalbest['Country'].isin(high_income_countries)) &
                                             (esr_hiy_globalbest['Year'].isin([2019, 2020, 2021]))]

# Focus on GBScores for QofL, Education, Food, Health, Housing, Work
GBScores_high = ['HiY_QofL_All_GBScore', 'HiY_Education_All_GBScore', 'HiY_Food_All_GBScore',
            'HiY_Health_All_GBScore', 'HiY_Housing_All_GBScore', 'HiY_Work_All_GBScore']
high_income_covid_rights = high_income_covid[['Country_Code', 'Country', 'High_Income_Country', 'Year'] + GBScores_high]

# Filter: all countries with missing data for all rights categories over ANY years of interest
# In case we want to look at all three years - we can't use a country that has no data for a year
high_income_missing = high_income_covid_rights.groupby(['Country', 'Year'])[GBScores_high].apply(lambda x: x.isna().all().all())
high_income_missing_countries = high_income_missing[high_income_missing].reset_index()['Country'].unique()
high_income_valid = high_income_missing[~high_income_missing].reset_index()['Country'].unique()
print('Unusable Countries')
print(high_income_missing_countries)
print('Valid Countries')
print(high_income_valid)
high_income_covid_rights_filtered = high_income_covid_rights[high_income_covid_rights['Country'].isin(high_income_valid)]

# For each right, count the number of countries that have complete data (it has data for all years for that right)
# Dictionary to store results
complete_counts_high = {}
# Loop through each rights column
for right in GBScores_high:
    # Group by country, check if all years have non-missing values for that right
    complete_per_country = high_income_covid_rights_filtered.groupby('Country')[right].apply(lambda x: x.notna().all())
    # Count how many countries have complete data (i.e., True)
    complete_counts_high[right] = complete_per_country.sum()
# Print results
high_income_country_counts_rights = pd.DataFrame(list(complete_counts_high.items()), columns=['HiY Right', 'HiY Num_Countries_Complete'])
print(high_income_country_counts_rights)

# Find proportion of all valid high income countries for each right
high_income_country_counts_rights['HiY Prop_Countries_Complete'] = high_income_country_counts_rights['HiY Num_Countries_Complete']/len(high_income_valid)

# Add 'right' column to high and low income country counts dataframes
right = ['Quality of Life', 'Education', 'Food', 'Health', 'Housing', 'Work']
high_income_country_counts_rights['Right'] = right
low_income_country_counts_rights['Right'] = right

# Merge high and low income
country_counts_rights = pd.merge(high_income_country_counts_rights, low_income_country_counts_rights, on = ['Right'])
display(country_counts_rights)

# Visualize counts
# Number of categories
x = np.arange(len(country_counts_rights['Right']))  # x positions for the categories
width = 0.35  # Bar width for each group

# Plotting the two-bar grouped bar plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

# Create bars for both groups
bars1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, country_counts_rights['HiY Num_Countries_Complete'], width, label='High Income', color='skyblue')
bars2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, country_counts_rights['LMY Num_Countries_Complete'], width, label='Low/Middle Income', color='salmon')

# Labels and title
ax.set_xlabel('Right')
ax.set_ylabel('Number of High vs Low/Middle Income Countries with Complete Data')
ax.set_title('Number of High vs Low/Middle Income Countries with Complete Data by Right')

# Set x-ticks and labels
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(country_counts_rights['Right'], rotation=45, ha='right')

# Add a legend
ax.legend()

# Layout adjustment
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

From the above data analysis, we decided to focus on the health and education rights, because these had the highest number of valid high income countries (and there were much less valid high income countries than low/middle income)¶

Insight 1: Comparing Right to Health by Income and Region¶

Insight Summary: Higher-income regions consistently score better on the right to health, exposing a stark divide in health equity that disadvantages low- and middle-income countries.

The figure above investigates global health disparities by comparing health scores over time (1990-2021) for the top 10 highest high-income and top 10 lowest low-income countries using Global Best Scores (GBScores). High income countries are represented by cool colors (e.g., greens and blues), whereas low income countries are represented by warm colors (e.g., yellows, oranges, and reds). Low-income countries show more volatile patterns with intermittent positive trends, suggesting recent improvements.

  1. Notable Insights from YoY Changes

Burkina Faso and Ethiopia show visible upward momentum in health scores, with occasional sharp increases not mirrored in high-income countries.

High-income countries (e.g., Finland, Austria) remain near a health performance ceiling, with plateau effects becoming apparent.

  1. Summary Statistics Reveal

High-income group: High mean, low standard deviation => stable, advanced health systems.

Low-income group: Increasing mean in recent years with persistent high variance => emerging but uneven progress.

  1. Insightful Patterns

Despite a persistent gap, some low-income nations are closing the distance incrementally.

Temporal clustering of growth in certain years (e.g., around 2015) may reflect coordinated global health initiatives or aid programs.

  1. Conclusion

While high-income countries maintain top-tier health scores, the real story lies in the growth patterns of certain low-income nations. These shifts offer a hopeful view into the potential impact of sustained health investments.

# COVID impact statistics
def calculate_covid_impact(df, country, score_column):
    country_data = df[df['Country'] == country]
    pre_covid = country_data[country_data['Year'] == 2019][score_column].mean()
    during_covid = country_data[country_data['Year'] >= 2020][score_column].mean()
    change = during_covid - pre_covid
    return {'country': country, 'pre_covid': pre_covid, 'during_covid': during_covid, 'change': change}

# Impact for all countries
high_income_impacts = [calculate_covid_impact(high_income_health, country, 'HiY_Health_All_GBScore')
                      for country in top_high_income_countries]
low_income_impacts = [calculate_covid_impact(low_income_health, country, 'LMY_Health_All_GBScore')
                     for country in bottom_income_countries]

# Visualization
high_income_impacts_df = pd.DataFrame(high_income_impacts)
low_income_impacts_df = pd.DataFrame(low_income_impacts)

print("\nCOVID Impact Analysis for High-Income Countries:")
print(high_income_impacts_df.sort_values('change', ascending=False))

print("\nCOVID Impact Analysis for Low-Income Countries:")
print(low_income_impacts_df.sort_values('change', ascending=False))

print(f"High-Income Countries: {high_income_impacts_df['change'].mean():.2f}")

Summary¶

This analysis provides more insight into the health score trends found among high and low/middle income countries. We hypothesized that culture, geography, and the broader political climate may play a role in overall health scores as well as COVID-19 response, and we decided to explore this by visualizing the average health scores and year-over-year changes by world region. We used data from 2000 till 2021 to investigate health scores both over an extended period of time, as well as during COVID-19. In order to preserve the accuracy of the aggregated calculations, these graphs only utilize data from countries that have reported health scores from all years between 2000 and 2021 (inclusive).

We used the regions and subregions found on the HRMI Rights Tracker website filter, with the exception of splitting "Americas" into "Northern America", "Middle America", and "South America" because of cultural/geographical/political differences in those regions.

Key Insights from Average Health Scores

  1. Sub-Saharan Africa was a consistently low outlier, scoring more than 10 points below the second-lowest-scoring region from 2020 to 2021. However, it also showed the most improvement throughout this time period, with a 20pt increase from 2000 to 2021.
  2. The rest of the regions showed gradual improvement over time, but collectively, their health scores stayed within the 65-85 range. Northern America consistently had the highest health scores, while the Pacific region was at the bottom of the pack for the majority of this time frame. South Asia entered the 21st century with health scores lower than the Pacific, but they experienced significant improvement throughout the next two decades.

Key Insights from Change in Health Scores

  1. For the most part, sharp positive and negative changes in health scores during specific years are not shared across regions, confirming that each region indeed undergoes unique challenges and successes in regards to health.
  2. The exception to this was the year 2020, during which the majority of regions experienced a significant drop in health scores, likely due to COVID-19. Interestingly, South Asia, the Pacific, East Asia, and Sub-Saharan Africa experienced a positive change in health scores between 2019 and 2020. One piece of information that we do not have is the exact point in the year during which these data were collected. This would help us theorize why this positive change occurred, as COVID-19 spread to different world regions at different times. For example, perhaps East Asia may have recovered earlier than other regions due to it being the pandemic's region of origin.
  3. Central Asia and the Pacific experienced a positive change in health scores between 2020 and 2021, whereas every other region experienced a decrease in health scores. Like the previous point, this could also be due to the timeline of data collection and measures utilized.

Key Takeaway: Taken together with the income comparison data, these graphs suggest that there may be complex, region-specific factors that affect a country's ability to provide for their citizens in the realm of health, especially in response to a global crisis such as COVID-19.

Insight 2: Comparing COVID-19 Death Rates by Right to Health Score¶

Insight Summary: Countries with similar health rights scores experienced vastly different COVID-19 death rates, suggesting that swift and effective policy responses mattered more than pre-existing health infrastructure alone.

# Fill missing new cases/deaths with 0
df['New_cases'] = df['New_cases'].fillna(0)
df['New_deaths'] = df['New_deaths'].fillna(0)

# Group by Country and Year, summing new cases and deaths
agg_df = df.groupby(['Country', 'Year'])[['New_cases', 'New_deaths']].sum().reset_index()

# Save to new CSV
agg_df.to_csv("WHO_Aggregated_By_Country_Year.csv", index=False)

print("Aggregation complete. File saved as 'WHO_Aggregated_By_Country_Year.csv'")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from matplotlib.patches import Patch

# Filter and clean
plot_data = esr_hiy_globalbest[esr_hiy_globalbest['Year'] == 2021].copy()
plot_data = pd.merge(plot_data, country_deaths, on='Country')
plot_data = plot_data.dropna(subset=['HiY_Health_All_GBScore', 'New_deaths', 'High_Income_Country'])
plot_data['High_Income_Country'] = plot_data['High_Income_Country'].astype(bool)

# Visual color map
plot_data['color'] = plot_data['High_Income_Country'].map({True: '#2c7c41', False: '#f1c40f'})  # deep green, gold

# Figure setup
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 12))

# Scatter plot
ax.scatter(
    plot_data['HiY_Health_All_GBScore'],
    plot_data['New_deaths'] / 100000,
    color=plot_data['color'],
    s=120,
    edgecolor='white',
    linewidth=0.8,
    alpha=0.85
)

# Highlight labels — only selected countries
highlight_countries = {
    'Low': ['Haiti', 'Mozambique', 'Burundi'],
    'Mid': ['India', 'Vietnam', 'El Salvador'],
    'High': ['Germany', 'Japan', 'France', 'Australia', 'United States of America', 'Brazil']
}
for group, countries in highlight_countries.items():
    for country in countries:
        row = plot_data[plot_data['Country'] == country]
        if not row.empty:
            x = row['HiY_Health_All_GBScore'].values[0]
            y = row['New_deaths'].values[0] / 100000
            ax.text(x, y + 0.15, country, fontsize=11, fontweight='medium',
                    ha='center', va='bottom', color='#333333')

# Trendline
sns.regplot(
    data=plot_data,
    x='HiY_Health_All_GBScore',
    y=plot_data['New_deaths'] / 100000,
    scatter=False,
    ax=ax,
    color='darkred',
    line_kws={'linestyle': '--', 'linewidth': 2}
)

# Styling
ax.set_title("Do Stronger Health Rights Lead to Better Pandemic Outcomes?", fontsize=22, weight='bold', pad=20)
ax.set_xlabel("HRMI Health Rights Score (2021)", fontsize=16)
ax.set_ylabel("Total COVID-19 Deaths per 100k (2021)", fontsize=16)
ax.set_xlim(40, 100)
ax.set_ylim(0, plot_data['New_deaths'].max() / 100000 * 1.15)
ax.tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=12)
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.6)

# Legend

This figure compares health rights scores in 2021 (from the HRMI dataset) to total COVID-19 deaths per 100K (from the external WHO dataset) for each country. Data points for high-income countries are colored green, whereas data points for low-income countries are colored yellow. Summary: Evaluating COVID-19 Deaths vs. HRMI Health Rights Performance (2021)¶

We wanted to see if stronger health systems are able to protect countries during times of crisis.

Methodology: We merged 2021 data from the Human Rights Measurement Initiative (HRMI) — which scores countries on how well they fulfill the right to health given their income — with WHO-reported COVID-19 death rates per 100,000 people. After cross-cleaning country names for consistency, we visualized this relationship to identify patterns in pandemic resilience.

What our data Shows:

  1. Stronger historical health performance did not guarantee better pandemic outcomes. Countries with the highest HRMI scores, like the United States and Brazil, also suffered the highest death rates.

Analysis: HRMI reflects real-world health rights fulfillment relative to national income — not legal intent, but execution. Yet even high performers failed when tested. Brazil delayed vaccine procurement, and the U.S. struggled with inconsistent public health messaging (The Lancet, 2021; JAMA, 2021). These failures weren’t about lacking capacity — they were about failing to mobilize it under crisis.

  1. Countries with mid-level HRMI scores outperformed wealthier peers by executing early, cohesive responses. Nations like Vietnam and Senegal, with moderate HRMI scores (65–75), reported very low COVID-19 mortality.

Analysis: These countries may not have historically maximized health rights, but they acted quickly and decisively during the pandemic. Success was driven by proactive containment, coordinated messaging, and strong community compliance — factors not captured in historical health performance, but essential in acute crises (BMJ Global Health, 2021; Nature, 2020).

  1. Among high HRMI scorers, trust and policy coordination shaped divergent results. Countries like Canada and South Korea, also top HRMI performers, experienced far fewer deaths than peers like the U.S.

Analysis: These governments deployed centralized public health campaigns, clear risk communication, and consistent containment policies. This led to higher compliance and lower mortality, despite similar starting points. This reinforces research from Health Affairs (2021) that institutional trust is critical in emergencies.

  1. HRMI performance is national — but health outcomes weren’t. The HRMI score does not account for within-country inequities, which shaped real-world mortality.

Analysis: In the U.S., COVID-19 death rates were 2–3x higher for Black and Indigenous populations than for white Americans. In the UK, low-income and racial minority communities suffered higher exposure and fatality rates. These disparities are invisible in national-level scores — yet deeply impacted outcomes.

High health system performance (as measured by HRMI) did not consistently translate into lower mortality. Instead, real-time governance, trust, and response agility mattered more than historical capability.

Insight 3: Comparing Health Right to Education by Income and Region during COVID-19¶

Insight Summary: Lower-income countries experienced much more dramatic changes in secondary education enrollment rates during COVID-19 than higher-income countries. On a broader level, most world regions experienced increases in enrollment rates alongside decreases in health right scores during COVID-19, suggesting that a general pattern of educational continuity during periods of health-related stress coexists alongside wealth-based differences in response.

Education Right: Secondary Education Enrollment Rate Data by Income¶

We decided to use secondary education enrollment rates to explore the right to education because out of the 7 indicators of right to education, the total net upper secondary school enrollment rate was the only indicator that was measured for both low/middle income and high income assessment standards.

Summary on Education Right Findings: Enrollment Rate Changes (2019–2021)¶

Our analysis of upper secondary enrollment rates across selected high-income and low/middle-income countries during the COVID-19 pandemic reveals several surprising patterns:

  • Unexpected Successes in Low/Middle-Income Countries: Countries such as South Africa, India, and Jordan achieved substantial increases in enrollment rates, defying expectations that lower income would necessarily mean greater educational disruption during the pandemic.

  • Severe Declines Not Limited to the Poor: Ukraine and the Dominican Republic, both low/middle-income, experienced the largest drops, but declines were also present in high-income countries, highlighting that wealth alone did not guarantee resilience.

  • Policy and Context Matter: These findings suggest that national policy responses, adaptability, and local context played a more decisive role in educational continuity than income group alone.

    • It is also important to keep in mind that other external factors may have played a role in educational continuity. For example, during this time period, Ukraine faced not only COVID-19 but also continued conflict with Russia that preceded the full-scale Russian invasion of Ukraine in early 2022. This could have negatively affected their steep drop in secondary education enrollment rate.

Key Takeaway: The COVID-19 pandemic was a stress test for education systems worldwide. Our results show that resilience and recovery in enrollment rates depended not just on a country’s wealth, but on its ability to adapt, innovate, and support students through crisis.

Summary¶

This graph compares changes in average health score vs changes in average secondary education enrollment rate by region from 2019-2021 in order to further explore the relationship between health and education during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The graph is split into four quadrants:

  • Top Left: Decrease in Health Score, Increase in Enrollment Rate
  • Regions: Middle East, South America, Europe, Northern America, East Asia, Sub-Saharan Africa, North Africa
  • The majority of the regions fall into this category, experiencing a decrease in health score as well as an increase in enrollment rate from pre- to post-COVID. This may indicate that these countries' education systems were able to withstand the effects of COVID, health-related and otherwise.
  • Top Right: Increase in Health Score, Increase in Enrollment Rate
  • Regions: South Asia, Pacific
  • These regions experienced an increase in health score from pre- to post-COVID alongside an increase in enrollment rate, suggesting that they may have responded to COVID more effectively than other regions.
  • Bottom Left: Decrease in Health Score, Decrease in Enrollment Rate
  • Regions: Middle America, Central Asia
  • These regions experienced a decrease in both health score and enrollment rate, possibly indicating that these countries' schooling systems were not equipped for the impacts of COVID-19.
  • Bottom Right: Increase in Health Score, Decrease in Enrollment Rate
  • Regions: None
  • No regions fell into this category, suggesting that better response to COVID-19 (here indicated by a positive change in health score during that period) did not come at the expense of education.

Combined with the analysis of education rights and income group, it is interesting to note that:

  1. The 5 high-income countries with the most dramatic enrollment rate changes are all in Europe. The fact that Europe's average change in enrollment rate was near 0 is reasonable, as 2 of those countries experienced increases while the other 3 experienced decreases.
  2. The 5 low-income countries with the most dramatic enrollment rate changes are all in different regions. This further points to the interaction between the global effects of COVID and the individual circumstances of various regions and countries at the time.

Key Takeaway: Regional differences in COVID-19 preparedness and education systems affected countries' ability to respond to and withstand the global crisis.
